<subSubSection id="8A7D56918EE3DA9098D3E1B5D796D97C" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="58C8550953C49F8A849C6AD7FCF69BCF" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="667B2EACD4E7CC2752A7B8198103B2D9" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Body weakly polished. Inner orbits almost parallel in females, weakly divergent downward in males. Antenna with 22-24 flagellomeres in females, 22-25 in males. Propodeum without rugae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6C7E3621E84AA833781BE49AA16DDB4A" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3D</figureCitation>
), without carinae except for anterior part of pleural carina. T I entirely coriaceous, rectangular in dorsal view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="13DFCF84BF11036007E42216C530429E" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Japanese Woldstedtius A, G. W. f. flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829); B, I. W. kuroashii (Uchida, 1957); C, D, K. W. takagii (Uchida, 1957); E. W. alpicola sp. nov.; F. W. biguttatus (Gravenhorst, 1829); H. W. karafutensis (Uchida, 1957); J. W. punctatus sp. nov. (E, J. holotype; B, I. paratype) - A, B. head, lateral view; C. head, frontal view; D. propodeum, lateral view; E-K. T I, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667929" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">9G</figureCitation>
). Latero-median carina of T I present basal ca. 0.5 of T I. Face black with a large yellow median spot in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D9739421E376F0A908104915C084FAE2" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3B</figureCitation>
), entirely yellow in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="253FD41170A5AE5AC97BCCC192B627EE" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3F</figureCitation>
). Lateral aspect of pronotum black with ventral and posterior yellow spots in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84EB6D62E74846D6AA83933D2353F025" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3A</figureCitation>
), black with yellow ventral and posterior areas in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E5B474CAD0DB34592F03BB97074E9D31" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3E</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron entirely black in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FF94F802DB08982FC0D3AA990217C34D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3A</figureCitation>
), black with a large yellow marking, it enlarged anteriorly in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E0A6365133956427BD72D010C9B9B800" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3E</figureCitation>
). Shoulder marks of mesoscutum yellow in both sexes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="ACF407EBB4B82B49AEBB7660907B1B7E" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3C, E</figureCitation>
). Scutellum black with an apical yellow spot in both sexes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="342CD119E0CB2D0AADAA9670F9A5B9F2" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3C</figureCitation>
). Hind coxa entirely orange in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F3FB4A63C3BA9484F7A81A466A51946C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3A</figureCitation>
), yellow with brown base in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7B009B1C8FAAD36DAFD930E01A7E734F" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3E</figureCitation>
). Hind trochanter yellow in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E59AC01C31A976E09F63561EE5BFFE57" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3A</figureCitation>
), yellow with a brown dorsal spot in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5B04FC862A6CD22188AE79CE9E3DF8A9" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Woldstedtius flavolineatus flavolineatus (Gravenhorst, 1829) (A-D. female; E, F. male) - A, E. Habitus; B, F. Head, frontal view; C. Mesonotum, dorsal view; D. Propodeum, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.69.80492.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/667923" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3E</figureCitation>
). Metasoma entirely black in females, bases of T III and T IV each with a transverse yellow band in males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="06791ECDAE6A61F74B1041328FEBE97E" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0563B8776FDCD94AA564B688F5222C58" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="28BC03457C6C5E17DF81DA6B59071DE2" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Japan (Hokkaido, Honshu, Shikoku, and Kyushu). Outside Japan, this species is widely distributed in Holarctic, Oriental, Oceanic, and Neotropical region (
<bibRefCitation id="353B12B447989BEC039973254764DCD4" author="Yu, DS" journalOrPublisher="Folia Entomologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" refId="B25" refString="Yu, DS, van Achterberg, K, Horstmann, K, 2016. World Ichneumonoidea 2015. Taxonomy, biology, morphology and distribution. [Database on flash drive]. Taxapad, Vancouver." title="World Ichneumonoidea 2015. Taxonomy, biology, morphology and distribution. [Database on flash drive]. Taxapad, Vancouver." year="2016">Yu et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="82DC1D0E5220F78199DE263634E5E081" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="bionomics">
<paragraph id="79E61B70DDFA5D1C0A0860AE3DDA78FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Bionomics.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7093BC8EC5A2D9D1DF9ED32B34F326E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
In Japan, one hover fly species, 
<taxonomicName id="8AE36CAA37974C8242D59E8260AD1A1A" baseAuthorityName="De Geer" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Episyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Episyrphus balteatus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balteatus">
<emphasis id="D9D0AA0ADCC36DD82F064E857E929B40" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Episyrphus balteatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(De Geer, 1776) is recorded as a host (
<bibRefCitation id="3D79CBDF324356F8ABF69FEAA85420B5" author="Uchida, T" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido University" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="226 - 265" refId="B23" refString="Uchida, T, 1957. Beitraege zur kenntnis der Diplazoninen fauna japans und seiner umgegenden (hymenoptera, Ichneumonodae). Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido University 50: 226 - 265" title="Beitraege zur kenntnis der Diplazoninen fauna japans und seiner umgegenden (hymenoptera, Ichneumonodae)." volume="50" year="1957">Uchida 1957</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="753EC14D71C7E787393E6F30D7493273" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="F714C8D3430D405F5EE63098AC4B0B5A" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="88CC9C2C0AA76EF65710709E29D8F18F" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
No additional specimen of this species from Japan was found in this study. Some or all previous records of this species from Japan may be based on misidentification of 
<taxonomicName id="3187883E636EF60B6E859FD46D81531E" genus="W." lsidName="W. biguttatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" rank="species" species="biguttatus">
<emphasis id="395FEDB53A99BB832433DD8CE539118D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">W. biguttatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
